3. Introduction
Our project aims to build an Advanced Mini Search Engine that retrieves information from local text files efficiently using advanced data structures.
The system reads multiple text documents, breaks them into words, and indexes them for fast searching.
Users can search for keywords or phrases, and the program displays the matching lines/documents instantly.
It will also provide autocomplete suggestions while typing and rank the search results based on frequency and relevance.
The systemâ€™s backend will be entirely implemented using C++ and data structures like Trie, Hash Map, Heap, and Hash Set.
A simple UI (if time permits) will be added for better interaction, but the core functionality will be console-based.
.
4. Motivation
We chose this project because searching through large files manually is inefficient and time-consuming.
In real life, search engines like Google and Bing handle massive data using complex algorithms and data structures.
Through this project, we aim to understand how search systems work at a smaller scale and how data structures make them faster and more efficient.
This project will help us strengthen our practical knowledge of DSAs such as Trie, Hash Map, and Priority Queue, and give us hands-on experience in solving real-world retrieval problems..
5. Real World use Casses
â€¢  Digital Libraries or Document Repositories
â€¢	Universities or organizations can use such a system to search across multiple academic files, books, or reports stored locally.
â€¢  Offline Knowledge Base or Note Search Tool
â€¢	Students or professionals can use it to search quickly through lecture notes or documentation without needing the internet.
â€¢  (Optional) Enterprise File Search
â€¢	In companies, employees could use a similar system to search keywords in project documentation or reports stored on internal drives.

6. Usage of Data Structures
Data Structure	Where Used	Why Used (Justification)
Trie (Prefix Tree)	For storing and retrieving words to provide autocomplete suggestions.	Tries enable O(m) prefix-based searching, which is faster than scanning all words.
Hash Map (Inverted Index)	Maps each word to the list of file names and line numbers where it appears.	Provides O(1) average lookup for keyword search, making it highly efficient.
Heap / Priority Queue	Used for ranking search results by word frequency or relevance.	Ensures quick retrieval of top-ranked results in O(log n) time.
Hash Set	Stores stop words (e.g., "the", "is", "a") that should be ignored during indexing and searching.	Avoids unnecessary processing and improves accuracy.
Array / Vector	Stores file content, lines, and search results dynamically.	Provides easy indexing and dynamic memory allocation.
